dataIdInfo.idAbs: As part of the QA/QC process for the CalSim 3.0 model, the georeference of the AutoCad Schematic was done by a private consultant. This process seems to have served its purpose as it has both demonstrated the inherent accuracy of the model and brought to light certain areas where some improvement may be realized. It was not possible to fully reference the schematic. The main challenge was that by necessity the model often represents groups of elements as single nodes. Consequently, all arcs designated "diversion, return, inflow, delta net depletion, spill, surface runoff or closure term" were considered conceptual and were not made to conform exactly to the features they represent, although they were placed as closely to those features as possible. This was about an 80% effort as time and budget were committed to referencing the entire schematic and stream channels only represented one portion of the model. The main goal here was simplicity for two reasons. The first was that, due to the reasons discussed above, these arcs are essentially conceptual in nature, often representing systems instead of single paths. Secondly, there was some discussion of creating a network form these data. The stream channels should remain fairly stable over the life of the model, but the demand units, diversions and returns may well vary considerably. This means that edits will become necessary in the future and manipulating networks while retaining topology will be simplified if the number of bends, vertices and crossings are kept to a minimum.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: These data were created to QA/QC the schematic layout of the CalSim 3 model. To date the model has been conceptual and schematic in nature. The process of georeferencing that schematic helps confirm the logical structure of the model.
dataIdInfo.idCredit: California Department of Water Resources, Modeling Support Office, Hydrology Development Group.

prcStep.stepDesc: In order to minimize the crossings of diversions to and returns from different conceptual features, their representations were kept as orthogonal as possible. Where that was impossible an attempt was made to at least maintain even half-angles (i.e. 45d and 22.5d). Even so there are a few examples that met neither of these criteria. In the case of channels (both stream and canal varieties) the actual centerline was used. Those centerlines were based on the hydrology data developed by ESRI based on the National Hydrography Dataset (NHD) and delivered with the ArcGIS software. After a review of the available stream centerlines from the NHD, the California Spatial Information Library (CaSIL) and the ESRI product, it was determined that the ESRI data were at least as accurate as the NHD, more accurate than other data available on CaSIL and had the added advantage of being readily queriable without large amounts of preprocessing. Even those data, however, often did not accurately reflect the current centerlines of the relevant streams and rivers. In the Central Valley streams tend to meander a great deal and as those changes affect mileages, the errant centerlines were corrected to available modern aerial imagery. Most often this was 2ft pixel imagery from AirPhotoUSA flown in 2006. Where that imagery was unavailable, older USGS DOQQs were used. These dated from the late 1990's, however they were only used on the periphery of the study area. Stream centerlines were then cut into mile long pieces, attributed, and further processed to extract mile points along the centerline. Those points were used to reference channel nodes from the model. The channel nodes were in turn used to split the original centerlines into channel arcs. Additional nodes were added to represent Water Treatment Plants, Wastewater Treatment Plants, Pump Stations and storage facilities (reservoirs). These were placed at their physical locations. Demand Unit nodes were added as close to their members as possible. CalSim III often represents several widely dispersed water users as a single node. Still other water users are themselves split across several geographic areas. As a result it was necessary to compromise on the locations of these nodes. There are also cases of exclusive groundwater users who return water via septic systems or percolation. In these cases an attempt was made to locate them reasonably close to the features the represent. However, as these nodes did not connect any arcs, they were moved as necessary to reduce the complexity of the schematic. Diversion and return arcs were then drawn connecting these demand units to their various sources and drains of water. Bypasses were also special cases. The Sutter Bypass is fairly well defined by its side canals, but the Yolo Bypass is much more enigmatic. Rather than come up with a unique centerline for these, we elected to use the USACOE delineation. The lines defining these two facilities run directly up their centers except for the downstream extreme of the Yolo Bypass which we aligned with the Lindsey Slough centerline. This was done to accommodate any future change in the way the Barker Slough diversion to the North Bay Aqueduct is depicted. Putah Creek and Cache Creek also had to be extended to meet the Yolo Bypass centerline. Those extensions followed existing water channels found in the aerials.
